	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64585727"><p><div class="quote"><p>Chevron deference allows courts to defer to federal agencies when there are disputes over how to interpret ambiguous language in legislation passed by Congress. That's supposed to lead to more informed decisions by leaning on expertise within those agencies. By overturning the Chevron doctrine, the conservative-dominated SCOTUS decided that judges ought to make the call instead of agency experts.</p></div><p>In other words, if the language of a law is ambiguous, a court gets to decide instead of some current group of political bureaucrats.
</p><p>Um<nobr> <wbr></nobr>... okay?  That's supposed to be scary?</p></div>
	</div>

